    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-10-08T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-10-08T19:00:00-05:00" n="92"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d92">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">398.051 <gloss target="#t_IFC1"
                    >IFC</gloss>/11–254: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative at the United Nations
                            (<persName type="from">Lodge</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">official use only</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-10-08T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 8, 1954—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Delga 77. Re: US position on <gloss target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss>. This telegram
                    has reference to International Finance Corporation and particularly to US
                    position which is in opposition to its establishment at this time. <gloss
                        target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss> discussed matter this morning and as result
                    urges that US position be changed so as to enable <gloss target="#t_USDel1"
                        >USDel</gloss> to sponsor with others resolution to authorize <gloss
                        target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> along lines suggested by <gloss
                        target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss> with other conditions acceptable to US to be
                    worked out in concert with participating governments.</p>
                <p>Senators Smith and Fulbright and delegates Jackson, Straus, Nash, Mahoney, Lord,
                    Johnson and Wadsworth and also Hotchkis support this position.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d92fn1">H. Alexander Smith, J. William Fulbright, C.D. Jackson,
                        Roger W. Straus, James Philip Nash, Charles W. Mahoney, Mary P. Lord, Ade M.
                        Johnson, James J. Wadsworth, and Preston Hotchkis.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In urging this change, delegation points out that under present world conditions:
                    1) <gloss target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> is sound in principle; 2) <gloss
                        target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> can be successfully operated with proper
                    safeguards; 3) <gloss target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> would be administered by
                        <gloss target="#t_IBRD1">IBRD</gloss>, as successful institution; 4) <gloss
                        target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> would serve to encourage free enterprise and
                    participation by private capital in under-developed countries; 5) <gloss
                        target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> would help to convince under-developed
                    countries that in a <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> organization US has their
                    welfare at heart in proposing means of access to secondary and equity financing
                    on approved businesslike projects.</p>
                <p>It is also suggested that possibility of securing US participation in <gloss
                        target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> by consent of Export-Import Bank to make
                    investment in <gloss target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss>, or as alternative to secure
                    consent of <gloss target="#t_FOA1">FOA</gloss> to make an investment in <gloss
                        target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss>, be explored.</p>
                <p>It is particularly urgent that our position be changed as now requested because:
                    1) US position on whole <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> agenda is
                    predominantly negative or neutral, and maintenance of our prestige and
                    leadership is thereby made more difficult: 2) US position on technical
                    assistance is neutral until further Congressional action; 3) there is growing
                    possibility that <gloss target="#t_SUNFED1">SUNFED</gloss>, under leadership of
                    Netherlands and backed by almost all under-developed countries, might well be
                    authorized at this session.<note n="2" xml:id="d92fn2">Preston Hotchkis, U.S.
                        Representative in the Economic and Social Council, followed up this telegram
                        with a letter addressed to Hauge, dated Oct. 28, 1954, which enumerated in
                        greater detail the reasons for the U.S. Delegation’s belief that the United
                        States should support the <gloss target="#t_IFC1">IFC</gloss> in principle.
                            (<gloss target="#t_E1">E</gloss> files, lot 60 D 68, “International
                        Finance Corporation, 1950–1956”)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lodge</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
